<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>1</sup>Harvey and Bernice Jones Eye Institute, University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences, Little Rock, Arkansas</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>2</sup>Department of Ophthalmology and Visual Sciences, Kellogg Eye Center, University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, Michigan</div>
<div id="A3">
<sup>3</sup>Bascom Palmer Eye Institute, University of Miami Miller School of Medicine, Palm Beach Gardens, Florida</div>
<div class="author-notes p">
<div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline"><strong>Corresponding Author:</strong> Krishna S. Kishor, MD</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="FN1">
<sup>*</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P1">Members of the SOURCE consortium include the following health systems (site principal investigators): <strong>Henry Ford Health System</strong>: Sejal Amin, Paul A. Edwards; <strong>Johns Hopkins University</strong>: Divya Srikumaran, Fasika Woreta; <strong>Montefiore Medical Center</strong>: Jeffrey S. Schultz, Anurag Shrivastava; <strong>Medical College of Wisconsin</strong>: Baseer Ahmad; <strong>Mount Sinai School of Medicine</strong>: Louis Pasquale; <strong>Northwestern University</strong>: Paul J. Bryar, Dustin D. French; <strong>Oregon Health Sciences University</strong>: Michelle Hribar; Merina Thomas; <strong>Scheie Eye Institute</strong>: Brian L. Vanderbeek; <strong>Stanford University</strong>: Suzann Pershing, Sophia Y. Wang; <strong>University of California-San Francisco</strong>: Michael Deiner; Catherine Sun; <strong>University of Colorado</strong>: Jennifer Patnaik, Prem Subramanian; <strong>University of Maryland</strong>: Saleha Munir, Wuqaas Munir; <strong>University of Michigan</strong>: Joshua D. Stein; Lindsey De Lott; <strong>University of Rochester</strong>: Rajeev Ramachandran; <strong>University of Texas-Houston</strong>: Robert Feldman; <strong>University of Utah</strong>: Brian C. Stagg, Barbara Wirostko; <strong>West Virginia University</strong>: Brian McMillian; <strong>Washington University</strong>: Arsham Sheybani; <strong>Yale University</strong>: Soshian Sarrapour, Kristen Harris-Nwanyanwu. The SOURCE Data Center is located at the University of Michigan. The Chief Data Officer of SOURCE is Joshua Stein. The Lead Statistician of SOURCE is Chris Andrews. More information about SOURCE is available at <a href="https://www.sourcecollaborative.org/" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">https://www.sourcecollaborative.org/</a>.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Issue date 2025 Mar-Apr.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC11930623  NIHMSID: NIHMS2035697  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39542214/" class="usa-link">39542214</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ogla.2024.10.010" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ophthalmol Glaucoma</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="S1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Purpose:</h3>
<p id="P2">To evaluate the risk of incidence rates of uveitis among patients starting topical glaucoma therapy.</p></section><section id="S2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Design:</h3>
<p id="P3">Retrospective database study utilizing the Sight Outcomes Research Collaborative (SOURCE) Ophthalmology Data Repository.</p></section><section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Participants:</h3>
<p id="P4">Adult glaucoma patients who were recently started on topical glaucoma therapy</p></section><section id="S4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods:</h3>
<p id="P5">Using data from 10 health systems contributing data to the SOURCE data repository, we identified all adult glaucoma patients who had been newly started on a topical glaucoma medication (prostaglandin analogues (PGAs), beta-blockers (BBs), alpha agonists (AAs), and carbonic anhydrase inhibitors (CAIs)). Patients with pre-existing documentation of uveitis were excluded.</p></section><section id="S5"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Main outcome measures:</h3>
<p id="P6">Incidence of uveitis within 3 months of initiating therapy with different topical glaucoma medications.</p></section><section id="S6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Results:</h3>
<p id="P7">We included 67,517 patients who were newly prescribed a topical glaucoma medication. The mean age of the patients was 67.3±13.2 years and ~59% were females. A total of 567 patients (0.87%) developed uveitis within 3 months of initiating the therapy. The incidence of uveitis was 0.32%, 1.95%, 1.63%, and 1.68% for users of PGAs, BBs, AAs, and CAIs, respectively. After adjusting for sociodemographic factors, individuals using topical BBs, AAs, and CAIs had significantly higher odds of developing uveitis versus those using PGAs (P&lt;0.001 for all comparisons).</p></section><section id="S7"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusions:</h3>
<p id="P8">The use of PGAs was not associated with higher odds of developing uveitis compared to other classes of topical glaucoma medications.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Glaucoma, prostaglandin analogs, uveitis, inflammation</p></section></section><section id="S8"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p id="P9">Glaucoma is a leading cause of irreversible visual impairment worldwide, and its prevalence increases with advancing age.<sup><a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>,<a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a></sup> Elevated intraocular pressure (IOP) serves as the main modifiable risk factor for the development and progression of glaucoma.<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a></sup> Various topical glaucoma medications are currently available to lower IOP, with topical prostaglandin analogs (PGAs) considered as the first-line choice for many types of glaucoma.<sup><a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a></sup> This preference is attributed to their efficacy in reducing IOP, convenient once-daily administration, and a minimal systemic side effect profile relative to other topical glaucoma medications.<sup><a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a></sup> The relationship between glaucoma medications and uveitis incidence is nuanced and has been the subject of considerable debate and investigation. PGAs, for instance, are commonly regarded as beneficial due to their efficacy and minimal systemic side effects but have been implicated in worsening intraocular inflammation in some studies.</p>
<p id="P10">Previous studies investigating the association between PGAs and uveitis have yielded conflicting results. Some reports suggest that PGAs may disrupt the blood-ocular barrier, potentially exacerbating intraocular inflammation,<sup><a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a>,<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a></sup> while other studies have found no clinically significant impact of PGAs on uveitis risk.<sup><a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>,<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a></sup> This inconsistency in the literature has led to uncertainty among clinicians regarding the safety of PGAs in patients susceptible to uveitis. Consequently, there is a need for large-scale, multicenter studies to provide more definitive evidence on the relationship between PGAs and uveitis. Despite the clinical importance, large-scale studies that explore the incidence of uveitis across different classes of glaucoma medications within diverse populations are scarce. Current literature is hindered by lack of robust evidence establishing a causal relationship between PGAs and uveitis leading to some ophthalmologists being hesitant to use PGAs in susceptible patients.<sup><a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a></sup> Most existing studies have limited sample sizes or focus on single centers, which could introduce bias and limit generalizability.</p>
<p id="P11">Utilizing a robust dataset from the Sight Outcomes Research Collaborative (SOURCE) Ophthalmology Data Repository—which encompasses health records from over 67,000 patients across ten academic health systems—this study is uniquely positioned to investigate these relationships. By providing a clearer understanding of the comparative risks associated with each class of glaucoma medications, this study aims to aid clinicians in making informed choices, thereby improving patient outcomes in populations susceptible to both glaucoma and uveitis. Such an evaluation aims to provide ophthalmologists with valuable insights, assisting them in making more informed decisions and facilitating discussions with their patients.</p></section><section id="S9"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Materials and Methods</h2>
<section id="S10"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Data Source</h3>
<p id="P12">We obtained data from the Sight Outcomes Research Collaborative (SOURCE) Ophthalmology Data Repository, which collects electronic health record (EHR) data from patients receiving eye care at academic health systems within this research collaborative. For the current study, ten active SOURCE sites contributed data spanning 5 to 12 years, including information on patient demographics, diagnoses identified through International Classification of Diseases (ICD) billing codes, findings from eye examinations during clinic visits, and details of prescribed outpatient medications. The data in SOURCE were de-identified, and privacy-preserving software (Datavant Inc.) allowed longitudinal tracking of patients across institutions while protecting their identities. SOURCE data have been used previously to study ocular diseases. More details about SOURCE are available at <a href="http://www.sourcecollaborative.org/" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">www.sourcecollaborative.org</a>.<sup><a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>−<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a></sup> The University of Michigan IRB approved this study with waived informed consent due to the retrospective and de-identified nature of the data. The study was conducted per the Declaration of Helsinki (version 2013).</p></section><section id="S11"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Inclusion and Exclusion Criteria</h3>
<p id="P13">We included all individuals aged ≥ 18 years with at least one ICD-9 or ICD-10 billing code for glaucoma and who were prescribed a topical glaucoma medication for the first time. To ensure that we captured the initial of treatment with each of these glaucoma medications, eligible patients needed a minimum 12-month healthcare system history with no record of topical medications before being prescribed the specific glaucoma medication of interest. Additionally, we required patients to remain in the healthcare system for a minimum of six months after the prescription of the glaucoma medication to fulfill our objective of examining the association between glaucoma medication initiation and the development of uveitis (<a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a>).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F1"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 1: Flowchart Outlining Patient Totals for Each Exclusion Criteria.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=11930623_nihms-2035697-f0001.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/3ee0/11930623/058b05124ca4/nihms-2035697-f0001.jpg" loading="lazy" height="1048" width="1050" alt="Figure 1:"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P45">STROBE-complaint flow chart detailing the number of patients excluded at each step of the data cleaning process.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P14">We excluded patients with a documented history of uveitis in the year before commencing a glaucoma medication. This was done to minimize confounding from recent or active uveitis that could influence both the choice of glaucoma medication and the risk of developing uveitis after medication initiation. Prior uveitis was ascertained using ICD-9 and ICD-10 diagnosis codes recorded in the electronic health records within the SOURCE data repository. Additionally, we excluded patients who were initially started on ≥ 2 glaucoma medications or a combination agent due to challenges in determining which agent(s) might be influencing the risk of uveitis. Furthermore, we excluded patients who underwent any ocular surgery in the year before or within three months after starting the glaucoma medication. As a secondary analysis, we performed the same analysis in patients with a history of chronic uveitis: recurrent iridocyclitis (364.02/H20.02x) and chronic iridocyclitis (364.1/H20.1x) (<a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Supplemental Table 1</a>). For this secondary analysis, we identified potential uveitis flares by the occurrence of new uveitis diagnosis codes after starting glaucoma medication. However, due to the limitations of the diagnostic codes, which do not specify disease activity or severity, we could not definitively distinguish between a flare of inflammation and the persistence of chronic uveitis.</p></section><section id="S12"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Outcome</h3>
<p id="P15">The primary outcome was identifying a new uveitis diagnosis within 3 months of starting treatment with the topical glaucoma medication. We identified the diagnosis of uveitis (anterior/intermediate/posterior/pan-uveitis) based on a comprehensive set of ICD-9 and ICD-10 codes. ICD-9 codes included 364.3, 364.04, 364.00, 364.01, 363.21, 362.18, 360.12, 363.00, 363.01, 363.03, 363.04, 363.06, 363.07, 363.10, 363.13, 363.15, 363.20, and 363.13. ICD-10 codes included H20.9, H20.04x, H20.00, H20.01, H30.2x, H35.06x, H44.11x, H30.01x, H30.02x, H30.03x, H30.04x, H30.14x, H30.89x, and H30.9x. See <a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Supplemental Table 1</a> for the full list of codes and their associated diagnoses, along with codes used to identify history of chronic uveitis.</p></section><section id="S13"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Statistical analysis</h3>
<p id="P16">We analyzed the data using R software, version 4.2. We summarized the patient characteristics using frequencies/precents and standard deviations (SD) for categorical and continuous variables, respectively. We examined those who had ≥1 record of uveitis within the first 3 months of initiating each of the four classes of topical glaucoma medications. We compared the proportion of patients who developed uveitis for the four classes using statistical tests, such as Pearson’s chi-square test, Fisher’s exact test, and non-parametric tests, such as the Wilcoxon rank sum exact test.</p>
<p id="P17">We fitted a logistic regression model to determine the odds of the development of uveitis within the first three months after starting topical glaucoma medication as the outcome. The primary predictor was the class of glaucoma medication prescribed to the patient. We adjusted the model for multiple covariates, including age at the glaucoma medication start date, gender, race/ethnicity, Distressed Community Index (DCI), and Rural-Urban Commuting Area Codes (RUCA). The DCI is a score that reflects the affluence level of the patient’s community of residence, considering factors such as unemployment rate, education level, poverty rates, and other economic indicators. It is scored from 0 to 100, with the higher the score the greater the level of distress of the community of residence.<sup><a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a></sup> RUCA captures the urbanicity of the patient’s community.<sup><a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a></sup> The significance level for all analyses was set at a p-value less than 0.05.</p></section></section><section id="S14"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h2>
<p id="P18">The current study included a total of 64,517 patients who met the eligibility criteria for inclusion. The mean age of the patients was 67.3±13.2 years. A total of 38,208 were females (59.2%) and 26,309 (40.8%) were males. The most common ethnicity was non-Hispanic, including 57,716 (89.4%) patients. There were 34,849 White patients (54%), 21,230 Black patients (32.9%), and 1,973 Asian American patients (3%). Most patients (53,073 patients, 82.2%) lived in urban communities. Among the 567 patients who developed newly diagnosed uveitis within 3 months, the mean age at first diagnosis was 62±15.9 years and included 327 females (57.6%), 316 (55.7%) White patients, and 190 (33.5%) Black patients. <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a> summarizes the baseline demographic characteristics.</p>
