<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="TFN1"><p id="P48"><em>Note</em>. SD, standard deviation; No., number/frequency; RUCA, Rural-Urban Commuting Area codes; DCI, Distressed Communities Index. The RUCA scores indicate the level of urbanization. The DCI score evaluates the economic wellbeing of a patient’s community.</p></div></div></section><p id="P19">In our cohort, a total of 567 patients (0.87%) developed newly diagnosed uveitis within 3 months of the start of topical glaucoma medications. The number (percentage) of patients who were newly prescribed PGAs, AAs, BBs, and topical CAIs, was 40,024 (62%), 10,787 (16.7%), 11,321 (17.5%), and 2,385 (3.7%), respectively. The number (percentage) of patients who developed newly diagnosed uveitis within 3 months of starting topical glaucoma medications was 130 (0.32%) for those prescribed PGAs, 221 (1.95%) for those prescribed BBs, 176 (1.63%) for those prescribed AAs, and 40 (1.68%), for those prescribed topical CAIs. The incidence of newly diagnosed uveitis within 6 months of the start of glaucoma medications was comparable to that within 3 months (<a href="#F2" class="usa-link">Figure 2</a>). The most common type of uveitis developed was anterior (84.7%), followed by posterior (10.2%), and lastly, intermediate uveitis (2.6%).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F2"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 2: Patients Developing Uveitis at 3- and 6-Months Following Drop Initiation.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=11930623_nihms-2035697-f0002.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/3ee0/11930623/550f8ac92b22/nihms-2035697-f0002.jpg" loading="lazy" height="626" width="1050" alt="Figure 2:"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P46">Percent of patients developing uveitis by drug class.</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P20">Logistic regression analysis revealed that the type of glaucoma medication a patient was newly prescribed was a statistically significant risk factor for uveitis. After adjustment for sociodemographic factors, compared to patients who were newly started on PGAs, those who had been started on BBs, AAs, and CAIs had 6-fold, 5-fold, and 6-fold higher odds of developing uveitis (p&lt;0.001 for all comparisons). We also found that Black patients had an odds ratio of 1.34 (97.5% CI, 1.07–1.67) of developing uveitis compared to other races (p=0.010) (<a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>). We subsequently examined the interaction of race (only Black and White) vs. glaucoma medication (Combine AA ,BB, CAI to “other). We found that this interaction was not statistically significant. Across the study period, the mean time for the development of uveitis was 47±53.3 days (median: 26.5 days) for PGAs, 38.2±52.8 days (median: 6 days) for BBs, 42.9±49.4 days (median: 23 days) for AAs, and 40.1±54.3 days (median: 16 days) for CAIs (<a href="#F3" class="usa-link">Figure 3</a>).</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T2"><h3 class="obj_head">Table 2.</h3>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P49">Logistic Regression of Factors Affecting Associated with Development of Uveitis at 3-Months Following Medication Initiation.</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="hsides" rules="groups">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
</colgroup>
