<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="TFN2"><p id="P50"><em>Note</em>. The variables under consideration include the type of glaucoma medication (with prostaglandin analogs, PGA, serving as the reference), race (with White as the reference), ethnicity (with non-Hispanic as reference) age, sex (with male as the reference), the Rural-Urban Commuting Area codes (RUCA, with urban areas as the reference), and the score on the Distressed Communities Index (DCI). The medications evaluated consist of alpha agonists (AA), beta blockers (BB), prostaglandin analogs (PGA), and carbonic anhydrase inhibitors (CAI).</p></div></div></section><figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F3"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 3: Time to Diagnosis of Uveitis by Glaucoma Drop Class.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=11930623_nihms-2035697-f0003.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/3ee0/11930623/3d1107b33417/nihms-2035697-f0003.jpg" loading="lazy" height="497" width="1050" alt="Figure 3:"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></figure><p id="P21">We lastly explored the rates of new uveitis in patients with a history of chronic uveitis. We found that the first glaucoma medication in patients with a history of chronic uveitis was BBs (42.4%), followed by AAs (34.5%), PGAs (14.4%), and CAI (8.63%). The percentage of patients who developed an acute flair of uveitis within 3 months of starting topical glaucoma medications was 0.35% for those prescribed PGAs, 2.4% for those prescribed BBs, 1.97% for those prescribed AAs, and 1.92% for those prescribed topical CAIs. The rates of new uveitis within 6 months of the start of glaucoma medications were also comparable to those within 3 months.</p></section><section id="S15"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Discussion</h2>
<p id="P22">We present the largest study to date examining glaucoma patients who newly started on topical glaucoma medications, aiming to evaluate the risk of development of newly diagnosed uveitis. Among the 64,517 patients who commenced topical therapy, the overall risk of uveitis was low, with 0.87% experiencing new uveitis within three months of initiating therapy. In comparing the incidence of uveitis across the various glaucoma medication classes, we observed that 0.35% of PGAs users developed uveitis, a rate lower than observed with other glaucoma medications (approximately 1.9–2.4%). Furthermore, after adjusting for the sociodemographic factors, the odds of uveitis were not higher for individuals prescribed PGAs in other glaucoma medication classes versus those prescribed other glaucoma medication classes. These trends remained in a secondary cohort of patients with a history of chronic uveitis.</p>
<p id="P23">Reported ocular side effects of PGAs include conjunctival hyperemia, hypertrichosis, and the potential reactivation of herpes simplex.<sup><a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a></sup> Some studies propose that PGAs may disrupt the blood-ocular barrier, potentially exacerbating intraocular inflammation and leading to uveitis and cystoid macular edema (CME).<sup><a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a></sup> However, contradictory findings exist, with several studies showing no definite impact of PGAs on uveitis or CME.<sup><a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a></sup> Arcieri and colleagues evaluated the effects of PGAs on the blood-aqueous barrier in patients with pseudophakic and aphakic glaucomatous patients using a laser flare meter. They reported that the mean flare values were statistically significantly higher in patients on PGAs compared to the control group receiving lubricant drops.<sup><a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a></sup> Another study by Smith and colleagues evaluated the association between topical latanoprost therapy and uveitis in 527 glaucoma patients. They showed that the incidence of uveitis is 1% in patients with no history of uveitis and 23% in patients with a previous history of uveitis.<sup><a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a></sup> Selen and colleagues showed a significant increase in the flare values with PGAs compared to patients receiving timolol or the control group who did not receive any medications, but these findings were not clinically significant.<sup><a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a></sup> Multicentric trials comparing latanoprost and timolol in patients with ocular hypertension and glaucoma, did not reveal an increased risk of intraocular inflammation in the latanoprost group.<sup><a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a>−<a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a></sup> Additionally, Fortuna and colleagues evaluated the flare-up rates in 42 uveitis patients treated with topical bimatoprost. They showed a lower risk of uveitis flare-up in patients on bimatoprost than those on other glaucoma agents; however, the difference was not statistically significant.<sup><a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">22</a></sup></p>
<p id="P24">Several smaller studies have shown that patients with uveitis or uveitic glaucoma treated with PGAs versus non-PGA agents had no difference in the frequency of anterior uveitis or development of CME.<sup><a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a>, <a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a></sup>. Chang et al.’s retrospective case series encompassing 163 eyes with uveitis and raised IOP treated with PGAs, showed no significant increase in the frequency of anterior uveitis compared to eyes treated with other IOP-lowering agents, affirming the safety profile of PGAs in clinically vulnerable populations.<sup><a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a></sup> This aligns with our observation that PGAs are associated with a lower incidence of acute uveitis, even in patients with history of chronic uveitis, reinforcing the argument that PGAs represent a viable option for patients with elevated IOP and a history of uveitis. One of us (Sallam et al.) conducted a retrospective analysis focusing on the management and outcomes of uveitis-related ocular hypertension.<sup><a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">25</a></sup> Findings from that work revealed that prostaglandin analogues, utilized in nearly half of the cases in the study (246 eyes), did not exacerbate uveitic inflammation. Additionally, a pilot study by Taylor et al. adds a novel dimension by investigating the impact of topical prostaglandin analogues on conjunctival inflammatory markers in patients (N=20) with uveitic glaucoma.<sup><a href="#R26" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R26">26</a></sup> Their findings that prostaglandin analogues do not significantly alter the expression of inflammatory markers provide a cellular and molecular basis for the clinical observed findings.</p>
<p id="P25">Our research contributes to a growing body of evidence that challenges the notion of PGAs as a potential risk factor for uveitis exacerbation in glaucoma patients with or without a history of uveitis, in diverse patient populations. The clinical implications of these findings are significant, calling for a re-evaluation of treatment paradigms of glaucoma, especially in those with pre-existing inflammation. In uveitis, the trabecular pathway is significantly more compromised due to inflammation, pigment dispersion, and potentially as a consequence of corticosteroid use, than the uveoscleral outflow pathway.<sup><a href="#R27" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R27">27</a></sup> This makes prostaglandin analogs (PGAs), with their predilection for the uveoscleral route, well-suited for lowering intraocular pressure in uveitis.</p>
<p id="P26">The current study has several limitations that warrant consideration. Firstly, similar to other database studies, our study is subject to different types of biases, including selection biases. Clinicians may have avoided prescribing PGAs to patients at risk of uveitis development—such as those with a prior history of uveitis or associated systemic conditions—due to concerns about potential exacerbation. This could lead to an apparent lower risk of uveitis among PGA users in our study, a phenomenon known as confounding by indication. Consequently, the lower incidence of uveitis observed with PGAs may partly reflect prescribing patterns rather than a true difference in risk. Secondly, the study’s retrospective nature may raise concerns about the accuracy of the billing codes used and the fact that we did not have access to clinical information on uveitis grading. The ICD-9 and ICD-10 codes we utilized do not provide detailed information on disease duration, severity, or activity status. While we attempted to identify patients with chronic uveitis using specific codes, the distinction between a flare of chronic uveitis and ongoing baseline inflammation remains unclear without clinical data. While potential misdiagnosis or miscoding for uveitis could impact the study findings, we believe this is unlikely to affect the results significantly and will be differential across different medication groups. We excluded eyes with a history of any ocular surgeries and those with a history of uveitis in the year before starting glaucoma medications; however, there may still be confounding factors, such as other ophthalmic conditions and systemic conditions or medications that were not adequately accounted for. The study’s results are confined to the 3–6 months following starting the glaucoma drops. Hence, the results cannot be extrapolated to long-term treatment or patients on multiple glaucoma drops. Patients who developed uveitis may have left the healthcare system shortly after diagnosis, potentially leading to underestimation of uveitis incidence. By requiring a six-month follow-up period, we aimed to reduce the likelihood of misattributing uveitis to other causes not accounted for in our analysis. While a large prospective randomized control trial is the benchmark for clinical research, the practicalities of enrolling a substantial patient cohort can pose significant challenges. An effective alternative approach might involve leveraging existing database studies as a foundation for constructing prospective cohort studies. Lastly, by excluding only those patients with a history of uveitis in the year prior to initiating glaucoma medication, we may not have accounted for patients with a more remote history of uveitis who might still be at increased risk of recurrence. This could potentially influence the observed incidence of uveitis in our study population. Future studies could explore the impact of a longer look-back period to assess prior uveitis history.</p>
<p id="P27">In conclusion, this multicenter study of patients newly started on topical glaucoma medications revealed that those prescribed PGAs were not associated with an increased incidence and risk of uveitis compared to other glaucoma medication classes. Additionally, PGAs did not increase the risk of uveitis in patients with a history of chronic uveitis. While the study does not pinpoint the specific factors driving the lower risk of uveitis among PGA users, it provided insight to re-evaluate the perception that PGA use is more likely to cause uveitis than other medications.</p></section><section id="SM1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Supplementary Material</h2>
